TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Challenge of Cultural Diversity: Harnessing a Diversity of Views to Understand Multiculturalism
AU  - Nemetz, Patricia L.
AU  - Christensen, Sandra L.
Y1  - 1996/04/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1996.9605060218
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1996.9605060218
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 434
EP  - 462
VL  - 21
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Formal diversity-training programs have been growing rapidly, but anecdotal literature suggests that many such programs garner negative reactions from participants. Charges of ?political correctness? and ?white-male bashing? may typify such responses. This article theorizes that fundamental beliefs and multiple sources of influence must be taken into account to predict a participant's reaction. Burrell and Morgan's (1979) work on paradigmatic differences is used to identify polar opposite beliefs about multiculturalism. Ideal states of multiculturalism are then defined and predicted from these fundamental beliefs. These belief systems are compared to sources of influence to predict reaction to a formal diversity-training program. We conclude with some cautionary dialogue about realistic expectations of diversity and the polarizing effects of Balkanizing rhetoric.
AB  - Formal diversity-training programs have been growing rapidly, but anecdotal literature suggests that many such programs garner negative reactions from participants. Charges of ?political correctness? and ?white-male bashing? may typify such responses. This article theorizes that fundamental beliefs and multiple sources of influence must be taken into account to predict a participant's reaction. Burrell and Morgan's (1979) work on paradigmatic differences is used to identify polar opposite beliefs about multiculturalism. Ideal states of multiculturalism are then defined and predicted from these fundamental beliefs. These belief systems are compared to sources of influence to predict reaction to a formal diversity-training program. We conclude with some cautionary dialogue about realistic expectations of diversity and the polarizing effects of Balkanizing rhetoric.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1996.9605060218
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1996.9605060218
Y2  - 2026/04/24
